15:22.623 --> 15:24.424
[ Dale ]
I am in.

15:26.927 --> 15:28.895
I'm in the nerve center.

15:28.962 --> 15:31.131
So where's Wayne Malloy, huh?

15:31.197 --> 15:33.066
You said you were gonna
bring him to me.

15:33.133 --> 15:36.136
I am.
I am all over his ass.

15:36.202 --> 15:38.772
But you can't even get into
a goddamn meeting.

15:38.839 --> 15:41.407
It's a‐‐
[ Sighs ]

15:41.474 --> 15:44.545
It's a very
high‐level meeting with
billionaires and such.

15:44.611 --> 15:46.947
You know what I hate, Dale?

15:47.013 --> 15:49.516
When somebody feeds me
a line of shit.

15:49.583 --> 15:52.819
All right.
All right. All right. Uh‐‐

15:52.886 --> 15:55.856
I'll pull a few strings.
I'll get in.

15:55.922 --> 15:58.091
I am in the loop.

15:58.158 --> 16:01.227
As we all know, in 2005,
Hurricane Katrina...

16:01.294 --> 16:03.597
laid waste to
the great city of New Orleans.

16:03.664 --> 16:06.867
Whole parts of the city
are still in ruins.

16:06.933 --> 16:11.304
Now it's time to rebuild.
Want to talk about
our vision, Doug?

16:11.371 --> 16:13.473
Absolutely.

16:16.176 --> 16:18.812
So, what we are planning...

16:18.879 --> 16:22.783
is a development that will be
a tribute to its
Louisiana heritage.

16:22.849 --> 16:27.120
Not just houses
and a golf course,
but an actual town center...

16:27.187 --> 16:30.323
that will be an exact
replica of the French Quarter.

16:30.390 --> 16:32.593
<i>Except not in New Orleans.</i>

16:32.659 --> 16:37.363
Exactly.
We are making a new New Orleans
right here in Ducaine.

16:37.430 --> 16:40.967
It will be called
Bayou Hills.

16:41.034 --> 16:44.237
Two hundred acres
of brand‐new houses,

16:44.304 --> 16:46.973
starting at $1.2 million.

16:47.040 --> 16:48.909
[ Felix ]
Excuse me, Doug.
Uh‐‐

16:48.975 --> 16:51.444
<i>Now, you cleared up</i>
<i>the problems with</i>
<i>the zoning permits, right?</i>

16:51.512 --> 16:53.747
<i>Hundred percent, Felix.</i>
<i>[ Clears Throat ]</i>

16:53.814 --> 16:57.884
We got clearance to build
on a former state park.
Pristine real estate.

16:57.951 --> 17:02.656
All we have to do is make 10%
of the homes affordable housing
for the Katrina refugees.

17:02.723 --> 17:05.325
Obviously, they'll have
their own parks and pools.

17:05.391 --> 17:08.929
The point is, we are helping
people here restart their lives.

17:08.994 --> 17:12.999
We're not just making money.
We are revitalizing
an entire community.

17:13.066 --> 17:15.135
‐ <i>[ Woman ]</i>
<i>Go right in.</i>
‐ <i>[ Felix ] Oh! It's Barry.</i>

17:15.201 --> 17:17.904
Barry?
Yeah.

17:17.971 --> 17:21.675
Excellent. I have some
legal documents that I'd like
everyone just to check out.

17:21.742 --> 17:25.811
They're on my desk.
I will just get them and be
back‐‐ right back‐‐ for Barry.

17:25.878 --> 17:28.147
‐ Excuse me one second,
gentlemen.
‐ There you go.

17:28.214 --> 17:30.517
Thank you.
I'm very sorry.

17:30.584 --> 17:33.887
I'm dead. He's comin' in‐‐
the guy from Princeton.

17:33.954 --> 17:36.322
Oh. How well
did he know Doug?

17:36.389 --> 17:38.692
Well, let's hope
it was a big class.

17:38.759 --> 17:41.394
Okay, hey, I gotta talk
to you about somethin'.

17:41.461 --> 17:45.131
Um, I'm in
kind of a situation,
and I gotta find another job.

17:46.533 --> 17:48.702
What?
Well, no‐no.
I know it sounds bad.

17:48.769 --> 17:51.304
But I'm really trying
to get us out from
underneath this thing.

17:51.371 --> 17:54.440
I keep thinking, if I just get
clear of this parole violation‐‐
Are you crazy?

17:54.508 --> 17:57.811
With the biggest deal
in our lives about to
blow up in our faces?

17:57.878 --> 17:59.746
Okay.

17:59.813 --> 18:02.949
You better focus here.

18:03.016 --> 18:05.285
This guy can bring us
both down.

18:05.351 --> 18:06.953
All right?
Okay.

18:07.020 --> 18:08.622
All right.

18:08.689 --> 18:10.624
[ Typing ]

18:12.693 --> 18:15.829
1,760,000 entries
for Barry Stone.
Shit.

18:15.896 --> 18:18.231
"Barry Stone, C. P. A."
"Barry Stone, dermatologist."

18:18.298 --> 18:20.834
"Barry Stone, C. P. A."
"Barry Stone...
for all your sewage needs."

18:20.901 --> 18:23.336
Sammi, give your mom everything
you got on Barry Stone.

18:23.403 --> 18:26.807
‐ Hey.
‐ I‐I can't find anything.

18:26.873 --> 18:28.942
‐ Oh, sh‐‐
What about a yearbook?
‐ "Princeton Univers‐‐"

18:29.009 --> 18:31.144
Well, I don't see one.

18:31.211 --> 18:35.148
What about a newspaper, Sam?
Like a Princeton newspaper.
Like‐‐ Keep lookin'.

18:35.215 --> 18:37.718
What the friggin' goddamn
hell are you doin'?

18:37.784 --> 18:40.020
<i>Minkov's reamin' my ass</i>
<i>on legal technicalities,</i>

18:40.086 --> 18:43.757
and Barry Stone is gonna
lose his shit if he doesn't
see his old friend Doug.

18:43.824 --> 18:46.459
Now get your ass in there
and reconnect.

18:52.298 --> 18:55.468
Here's the Dougmeister.
Hey!

18:57.804 --> 18:59.472
Barry.

18:59.540 --> 19:02.976
Doug?
Oh, my God. You look
completely different.

19:03.043 --> 19:05.011
I‐I'd have never
recognized you.

19:05.078 --> 19:06.847
‐ [ Both Laugh ]
‐ <i>[ Barry ] Hey.</i>

19:06.913 --> 19:10.050
Hi, Hugh.
<i>[ Wayne ] Oh, my God,</i>
<i>we must be getting old.</i>

19:10.116 --> 19:13.554
<i>River of life, man.</i>
<i>[ Barry ]</i>
<i>Why, yeah. I might have‐‐</i>

19:13.620 --> 19:17.457
I might have lost
a few hairs and put on
a couple of pounds of‐‐

19:17.524 --> 19:20.126
I‐‐ I‐‐
You do not at all...

19:20.193 --> 19:22.629
look like you used
to look.

19:22.696 --> 19:24.397
No.
I mean,

19:24.464 --> 19:26.967
didn't you
used to be kind of‐‐
It's a rug, man. Be cool.

19:27.033 --> 19:29.202
Oh!
[ Stammers ]

19:29.269 --> 19:33.073
So I'm not completely
senile, I mean‐‐
No. Yeah, I remember you,

19:33.139 --> 19:35.241
'cause you‐you, uh‐‐

19:36.309 --> 19:38.945
The police got you.

19:39.012 --> 19:41.982
I cannot believe you have
the gall to bring that up.

19:42.048 --> 19:45.619
No.
How was I supposed to know
she was just 15?

19:45.686 --> 19:48.288
No. No one knew.
It was‐‐ She looked 40.

19:48.354 --> 19:51.992
<i>Yeah, well, at least</i>
<i>I wasn't known as</i>
<i>the campus coke dealer.</i>

19:52.058 --> 19:55.095
No, you weren't.
No.

19:55.161 --> 19:56.863
I was.

19:56.930 --> 20:00.200
Th‐This is boring the shit
out of everyone, so, uh‐‐

20:00.266 --> 20:02.168
It's good to see you again.
Yeah.

20:02.235 --> 20:03.770
So excellent.
Yeah.

20:03.837 --> 20:06.406
On with the deal, gentlemen.
Rock and roll.

20:06.472 --> 20:08.108
[ Laughing ]
Onward.

20:08.174 --> 20:11.444
‐ [ Chuckles ]
‐ [ Felix ] Jesus. Fifteen?

20:11.512 --> 20:13.680
[ Wayne ]
Let's do the deal, gentlemen.
[ Barry ] Yes.

20:13.747 --> 20:18.519
‐ [ Men Murmuring ]
‐ [ Barry ] She was‐‐
She was‐‐ She was 18.

20:18.585 --> 20:22.589
Absolutely.
I've got no problem
with raw fish.

20:22.656 --> 20:24.891
No. Yeah.

20:24.958 --> 20:27.961
Well, there is one thing
that I should tell you‐‐
that I should clear up.

20:29.796 --> 20:32.799
In the, uh‐‐
In the recent past, I‐I was
convicted of a crime,

20:32.866 --> 20:34.835
and I did spend some‐‐

20:36.703 --> 20:39.039
Oh, then you know
how it is.

20:39.105 --> 20:42.643
Huh. Well‐‐

20:42.709 --> 20:45.946
Oh, thank you.
Thank you, Travis.

20:46.012 --> 20:49.349
That's great.
Yeah. Uh‐‐

20:49.415 --> 20:52.352
Well, I can come by tom‐‐

20:52.418 --> 20:55.455
Now? Well, n‐‐ now's not
such a good time.

20:57.157 --> 20:59.793
Right. No, m‐my personal life's
not gonna be a problem.

20:59.860 --> 21:02.095
No, I promise.

21:02.162 --> 21:03.997
Nah, I'll be there
right away.

21:08.268 --> 21:12.238
So that about covers
financing.

21:12.305 --> 21:14.340
Are there any questions?

21:14.407 --> 21:16.877
[ Clears Throat ]
Yeah.

21:16.943 --> 21:20.781
I would like to know
exactly why these
deal papers...

21:20.847 --> 21:25.719
make no mention
of applying for C. D. B. G.'s
or U. S. E. D. A.'s.

21:25.786 --> 21:27.821
Hugh?

21:27.888 --> 21:30.190
Doug, that's your arena.

21:30.256 --> 21:33.159
Yes.

21:33.226 --> 21:35.596
Sorry to interrupt,
gentlemen,

21:35.662 --> 21:38.264
<i>but I thought you'd be</i>
<i>interested to know...</i>

21:38.331 --> 21:42.769
that we have fresh brewed
coffee available
in the coffee room.

21:42.836 --> 21:44.605
Thank you, Dale.

21:44.671 --> 21:47.440
‐ Mmm.
‐ You may go.

21:47.508 --> 21:51.512
‐ But it is an excellent idea.
‐ Is that the handyman?

21:51.578 --> 21:57.250
Yes, he's part of our program
for hiring people of, uh‐‐
of little worth, wherewithal‐‐

21:57.317 --> 21:59.385
He's, uh, right though.

21:59.452 --> 22:03.056
There is coffee there,
so if we want to break, we can
get a nice brewed coffee.

22:03.123 --> 22:05.526
Roast.
Doug?

22:05.592 --> 22:09.029
Yes?
C.D.G.B.'s‐‐ I'd like
an explanation, please.

22:09.095 --> 22:11.565
Yes. I think that's important.

22:11.632 --> 22:13.734
‐ Um‐‐
‐ <i>[ Cell Phone Buzzes ]</i>

22:13.800 --> 22:17.504
I am so sorry.
Someone's calling me.

22:17.571 --> 22:21.975
God, this is terrible.
Um, C. D. G. B.'s.

22:22.042 --> 22:26.813
They don't apply
to parkland, Barry.
You can't, uh, make application.

22:26.880 --> 22:29.816
It's the Community Development
Block Grant‐‐

22:29.883 --> 22:33.687
can only, uh, apply
to pre‐existing communities,
I think you'll find.

22:33.754 --> 22:38.659
‐ I see. What about an H. A. P.?
‐ You're putting me through
my paces now. H. A. P.'s.

22:38.725 --> 22:41.161
H.A.P.'s. They are
a different kettle of fish,

22:41.227 --> 22:46.567
'cause you've got to be
a, uh‐‐ a 501‐C3,
as you'll know.

22:46.633 --> 22:49.435
‐ 501‐C‐‐ What?
‐ What the hell does that mean?

22:49.503 --> 22:52.606
‐ What does it mean?
Sounds like a pair of jeans.
‐ [ Beeps ]

22:52.673 --> 22:57.277
But it, in fact,
is a registered nonprofit.

22:57.343 --> 23:00.714
‐ [ Clicks Tongue ]
Not us.
‐ <i>[ Men Murmuring ]</i>

23:02.683 --> 23:04.751
You're not a lawyer, are you?

23:06.319 --> 23:10.023
No, I'm... not a lawyer.
You're a lawyer.

23:10.090 --> 23:12.325
No. Yes, I am.

23:12.392 --> 23:15.596
‐ But I know people who aren't.
‐ [ Woman ]
What's he talking about?

23:20.500 --> 23:23.937
<i>Oh, wait. Well, no, no.</i>
<i>You don't cut</i>
<i>the head off first.</i>

23:24.004 --> 23:27.774
You cut the fin out first,
and‐‐ and then you rip
the guts out.

23:27.841 --> 23:30.143
I thought you said
you knew fish.
I do.

23:30.210 --> 23:35.215
I just‐‐ I find it easier
if I cut the head off first...

23:35.281 --> 23:38.519
to get to the guts.

23:38.585 --> 23:42.756
You cut the head off first,
the whole fish falls apart.
Here. Here. Don't screw up.

23:42.823 --> 23:45.425
Okay, I won't.
I swear.

23:45.491 --> 23:49.696
So, um, you've done
some time, huh?

23:49.763 --> 23:52.766
Yeah, it was just
a white collar thing.

23:52.833 --> 23:55.636
‐ Two years.
‐ <i>[ Knife Clangs ]</i>

23:57.203 --> 24:01.474
It was
a maximum security prison.
Very overcrowded.

24:01.542 --> 24:04.044
Lot of fights.
[ Exhales ]

24:05.846 --> 24:10.951
As a matter of fact,
I knocked somebody's teeth out
once with a cafeteria tray.

24:11.017 --> 24:12.786
Been there, done that.

24:15.522 --> 24:17.824
Okay, so, um, you can have
the graveyard shift.

24:19.693 --> 24:23.329
6:00 to midnight.
No benefits, no overtime.

24:23.396 --> 24:27.768
You don't show up, you're fired.
You call in sick, you're fired.
You come late, you're fired.

24:27.834 --> 24:30.504
[ Clears Throat ]
So you live near here?

24:30.571 --> 24:32.773
Nah. I'm lookin'
for a place.

24:32.839 --> 24:35.041
Yeah, well,
there's a vacancy
in my building.

24:35.108 --> 24:38.078
Guy‐‐ Guy down the hall
from me passed.

24:38.144 --> 24:40.213
‐ Yeah, you probably
whacked him.
‐ Okay, know what?

24:40.280 --> 24:43.049
Why don't you just
shut your mouth?
All right?

24:43.116 --> 24:46.687
Disrespectful mother‐‐
I'm trying to help
the lady out here.

24:48.655 --> 24:50.691
Welcome to the team.

24:52.626 --> 24:55.295
♪♪ Ma'am, did you never hear ♪♪

24:55.361 --> 24:57.564
♪♪ Of pretty Molly Brannigan ♪♪

24:57.631 --> 24:59.900
♪♪ In truth
then she left me ♪♪

24:59.966 --> 25:02.569
♪♪ I'll never be a man again ♪♪

25:02.636 --> 25:04.805
♪♪ Not a touch on me hide ♪♪

25:04.871 --> 25:07.508
♪♪ Will the summer sun
e'er tan again ♪♪

25:07.574 --> 25:10.310
♪♪ 'Cause Molly's left me ♪♪

25:10.376 --> 25:14.014
♪♪ A lonely guy ♪♪♪♪

25:15.481 --> 25:17.584
Thank you.

25:18.719 --> 25:22.255
‐ Oh, shit.
‐ Just don't make eye contact.

25:22.322 --> 25:27.994
Oh, my God.
This is so sad.
They're begging.

25:32.365 --> 25:34.601
Thanks, bitch.

25:43.009 --> 25:45.746
I'm a little concerned
about our tax liability...

25:45.812 --> 25:48.281
once the Section 8
housing is eliminated.

25:48.348 --> 25:52.018
Well, that's a nonissue.
We're not gonna eliminate
the affordable housing.

25:52.085 --> 25:54.655
Doug, let's cut
the bullshit, okay?
This is not bullshit.

25:54.721 --> 25:59.926
The city would never give us
public land unless we make 10%
of it affordable housing.

25:59.993 --> 26:03.063
Shit, 15% of our funding
is from FEMA.
Yeah, I know, I know.

26:03.129 --> 26:05.866
I read the deal memo,
but we had a verbal
understanding, right?

26:05.932 --> 26:08.802
‐ What verbal understanding?
‐ See, the thing‐‐

26:08.869 --> 26:12.739
Nobody paying a million dollars
for a house is gonna want
to live near poor people.

26:12.806 --> 26:14.975
The low‐income housing
will have its own area.

26:15.041 --> 26:18.579
Stop the bullshit, Doug.
I can show you
the blueprints.

26:18.645 --> 26:22.849
Doug. Doug.
I might have forgotten
to mention a minor detail,

26:22.916 --> 26:25.652
which is that, uh,
you're right, Felix.

26:25.719 --> 26:30.023
We had a verbal agreement
that the construction will go
in three phases.

26:30.090 --> 26:34.528
<i>Phase One‐‐</i>
<i>we build the luxury homes.</i>

26:34.595 --> 26:38.799
Phase Two‐‐ we sell
all the luxury homes.

26:40.200 --> 26:43.570
And then the rich
Phase Two homeowners...

26:43.637 --> 26:48.474
band together
and rule out Phase Three.

26:48.542 --> 26:50.410
So, actually, Phase Three
never happens.

26:50.476 --> 26:53.446
'Cause you're right, Felix.
Nobody's gonna pay
a million bucks...

26:53.514 --> 26:56.950
to live cheek by jowl
with the Phase Three element.

26:57.017 --> 26:59.520
[ Wayne ] You did kind of
forget to mention that.
<i>Uh, yeah.</i>

26:59.586 --> 27:02.823
Oh, the city will be yellin'
and screamin'. There'll be
lawsuits up the wazoo.

27:02.889 --> 27:04.825
But our legal team
will handle that.
Right, Doug?

27:04.891 --> 27:09.029
Hey, hey. Just wanted
to make sure we're clear
on the terms of the deal.

27:09.095 --> 27:11.532
You know? Right?
<i>We're clear.</i>

27:11.598 --> 27:15.802
Are we clear on
the terms of the deal?

27:15.869 --> 27:20.240
Can you, you know, guarantee
no Phase Three, Doug?

27:25.946 --> 27:27.714
Yeah.

27:27.781 --> 27:30.116
No Phase Three.

27:30.183 --> 27:32.418
Let's sign the deal.
[ Hugh ]
All right!

27:32.485 --> 27:35.722
[ Laughter ]
I got a couple cases of
champagne on ice in the atrium.

27:35.789 --> 27:40.126
How 'bout we crack 'em open?
[ Felix ] I thought
you would never ask.

27:40.193 --> 27:43.129
Doug, this guy named Chet
has called for you twice.

27:43.196 --> 27:46.933
He's looking for someone
named Pete Mincey?

27:52.739 --> 27:54.841
<i>[ Door Closes ]</i>

28:05.318 --> 28:08.121
Thanks for saving my ass
in there.
You're welcome.

28:08.188 --> 28:11.057
I quit.

28:11.124 --> 28:15.562
No, no. H‐Hang on.
J‐Just give me‐‐
Just give me a couple minutes.

28:15.629 --> 28:17.764
Just‐‐

28:20.801 --> 28:22.803
Yes, I know, I know.

28:22.869 --> 28:25.105
I had problems passing
the bar exam‐‐

28:25.171 --> 28:27.908
I don't give a shit
that you're not a lawyer.
Okay?

28:27.974 --> 28:30.544
I figured that out
a long time ago,
but I didn't care.

28:30.611 --> 28:35.281
I liked you. In this whole
crazy, sick place, you were
the only person who seemed real.

28:35.348 --> 28:38.952
Right. Well, if it's any
consolation, my son thinks
I'm an asshole too.

28:39.019 --> 28:41.688
Do you even get what just
happened in that meeting?

28:41.755 --> 28:44.224
This is fraud, Doug.
Or Wayne.

28:44.290 --> 28:46.459
Or whatever the hell
you call yourself.

28:46.527 --> 28:50.030
And you are using the tragedy
of thousands of people as
a cheap trick to make money.

28:50.096 --> 28:52.132
No‐‐
And then you're
screwing those people.

28:52.198 --> 28:55.101
No, we're not screwing them.
We will build
the affordable housing.

28:55.168 --> 28:57.771
Don't bullshit me, Wayne!
No, no‐‐
I'm not bullshitting you.

28:57.838 --> 29:00.340
We are bullshitting
the investors.
That's what you do in a deal.

29:00.406 --> 29:03.076
You say whatever you want
to say in order
to close the deal,

29:03.143 --> 29:05.445
then you do
what you wanted to do
in the first place.

29:05.512 --> 29:09.382
Tha‐That's sales.
That's what you do.
You know that.

29:09.449 --> 29:11.885
Why should I believe you?

29:11.952 --> 29:17.123
'Cause if I don't
build it, then you can
turn me over to the cops.

29:19.359 --> 29:23.229
And because
I need to believe me.

29:24.898 --> 29:28.769
Hey, better come to the party
before Hugh drinks
all the champagne.

29:28.835 --> 29:31.505
All right. Okay.
[ Door Closes ]

29:35.676 --> 29:37.678
I‐‐
[ Door Opens ]

29:37.744 --> 29:41.715
Forty, 60.
One, two, three, four, five.

29:41.782 --> 29:43.984
Sixty‐five.

29:44.050 --> 29:47.688
Probably get to a hundred,
you stop eatin' those
five‐dollar frozen yogurts.

29:47.754 --> 29:49.556
Oh, yeah?
Yeah.

29:52.626 --> 29:55.095
You don't want
to do this anymore.
Let's get something to eat.

29:55.161 --> 29:58.599
No, I do.
I want to.

29:58.665 --> 30:00.734
Oh, come on.

30:00.801 --> 30:02.736
Like I care what those
buffer assholes think.

30:02.803 --> 30:05.138
Never used to.
[ Chuckles ]

30:05.205 --> 30:08.274
[ Laughs ]

30:14.047 --> 30:16.517
Ah, shit, Di.
Come on.

30:18.418 --> 30:21.187
[ Sighs ]
I can't do this
anymore, Cael.

30:21.254 --> 30:25.025
Hey, look.
It's okay.
No, it's not.

30:29.462 --> 30:32.098
Cael, I want it to be
like it always was.

30:32.165 --> 30:35.702
It can be.
No, Cael.

30:35.769 --> 30:37.704
It can't.

30:37.771 --> 30:39.773
Why not?

30:39.840 --> 30:42.442
Why, 'cause I hate it here?

30:44.110 --> 30:46.379
'Cause I like it.

30:49.249 --> 30:52.986
[ Sighs ]

30:53.053 --> 30:55.055
I got an English paper
due tomorrow.

30:55.121 --> 30:58.191
I gotta go home, so‐‐

31:03.063 --> 31:05.065
Let's not
do good‐byes, all right?

31:07.100 --> 31:09.970
I hate good‐byes.

31:13.206 --> 31:15.942
It's not like
I'm not gonna see you again.

31:16.977 --> 31:19.412
[ Baby Crying ]

31:19.479 --> 31:22.382
♪♪♪♪ [ Music In Background,
Faint ]

31:24.484 --> 31:26.452
So he O. D.'d?

31:26.520 --> 31:28.955
Yeah, right there
on the Barcalounger.
Hmm.

31:29.022 --> 31:33.126
Was watchin' Survivor.
Kind of a cruel twist
of fate if you ask me.

31:33.193 --> 31:35.095
You can keep the chair
if you want.

31:35.161 --> 31:37.864
And the toaster oven too.

31:37.931 --> 31:42.268
But I hope you heard me
loud and clear.
No turnin' tricks here.

31:42.335 --> 31:44.638
I told you.
I'm not a hooker.

31:44.705 --> 31:47.440
I'm not here to judge.
I just don't want no trouble.

31:47.508 --> 31:51.812
Ain't gonna be no trouble.
My application.

31:51.878 --> 31:54.147
Okay.
License.

31:56.683 --> 32:00.220
"Dahlia Malloy."
That's a real
pretty name.

32:00.286 --> 32:03.256
Yeah, I always thought so.

32:03.323 --> 32:06.292
Well, I hope
you're happy here,
Dahlia Malloy.

32:06.359 --> 32:08.529
Lance was.

32:09.996 --> 32:12.265
Maybe that was just the crack
talkin', huh?

32:15.902 --> 32:18.438
[ Chattering, Laughter ]

32:18.505 --> 32:20.774
Thank you.

32:20.841 --> 32:23.409
Huh.
[ Whispers ]
It's all right.

32:24.678 --> 32:28.281
What makes you hard,
Barry? Hmm?
What?

32:28.348 --> 32:31.685
Mmm? What turns you on?
What floats your boat? Huh?

32:31.752 --> 32:34.054
Hookers? Huh? Car?

32:34.120 --> 32:37.190
Underage girl?
Oh‐‐

32:37.257 --> 32:39.192
[ Laughs ]
[ Forced Laugh ]

32:39.259 --> 32:41.227
Gentlemen.
Oh, Felix, uh‐‐

32:41.294 --> 32:44.598
Mmm! Barry, drink up.
Drink up there.

32:44.665 --> 32:47.968
Look at all this champagne
I got here. Come on.
It's beautiful.

32:48.034 --> 32:51.972
[ Hugh ] Havin' fun?
[ Barry ] Yeah,
just great. Thank you.

32:56.743 --> 32:58.845
[ Groans ]

32:58.912 --> 33:00.847
Hugh's having fun, huh?

33:00.914 --> 33:03.049
Hugh likes money.
Oh, yeah.

33:04.184 --> 33:06.720
Yeah. You'll cut him
out of the deal.

33:06.787 --> 33:08.755
What?

33:08.822 --> 33:11.758
Doug, you'll be so betrayed
when you find out
he's been embezzling.

33:11.825 --> 33:13.860
[ Scoffs ]

33:13.927 --> 33:15.796
What the hell
are you talking about?

33:15.862 --> 33:18.498
Relax, Doug.
Relax.

33:18.565 --> 33:22.002
After he goes to jail,
you and I will split
the profits.

33:22.068 --> 33:24.404
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.

33:24.470 --> 33:28.575
Just after we,
uh, sprout wings
and fly to the moon.

33:28.642 --> 33:30.744
Got it.
Okay.

33:32.145 --> 33:35.081
Or‐Or maybe, uh‐‐

33:35.148 --> 33:38.585
Maybe I should rip off...

33:38.652 --> 33:41.788
your goddamn rug!

33:41.855 --> 33:43.790
Ooh! Oh, my God.

33:43.857 --> 33:48.729
That's a very high‐quality
toupee you've got here, Doug.
[ Groans ]

33:48.795 --> 33:51.131
You Americans make
the best...

33:51.197 --> 33:54.200
fakes ever!
[ Grunts ]

33:54.267 --> 33:56.637
Now, you think
I couldn't tell...

33:56.703 --> 33:58.872
you never went to
Princeton, you prick?

33:58.939 --> 34:02.242
My partner may be stupid,
but I'm not.

34:02.308 --> 34:06.780
Now, I don't give shit
who you really are, Doug.

34:06.847 --> 34:11.351
For me, you're a guy who knows
how to make money, like me.

34:11.417 --> 34:15.556
So you'll set him up,
and we'll split the profits.

34:15.621 --> 34:18.391
It's a win‐win. Okay?

34:18.458 --> 34:20.527
[ Groans ]

34:21.762 --> 34:25.130
♪♪♪♪ [ Disco ]

34:26.331 --> 34:29.268
Except for Hugh.
Huh?

34:33.306 --> 34:35.308
I'll take that as a yes.

34:39.245 --> 34:44.717
♪♪♪♪ [ Continues ]

34:44.784 --> 34:46.620
<i>[ Line Rings ]</i>

34:46.687 --> 34:49.623
[ Man ]
Yeah?
Yeah, this is Dale Malloy.

34:49.690 --> 34:52.826
Quinn said you'd be
expecting my call.

34:52.893 --> 34:55.862
Well, if you're gonna
bring your man in,
I got the numbers you need.

34:55.929 --> 34:57.531
All right.

34:57.598 --> 35:01.234
This is Officer Devereaux.
Leave a message.
[ Beep ]

35:01.301 --> 35:04.738
Hi, Officer Devereaux.
This is Dahlia Malloy.

35:04.805 --> 35:08.141
I'm, uh, just leaving you
this message...

35:08.208 --> 35:11.444
'cause it's, uh, 6:30,

35:11.512 --> 35:15.148
and so you don't have to
put out that warrant
for my arrest...

35:15.215 --> 35:19.285
because I'm working
in the kitchen
at Rudy and Flo's Fish Shack,

35:19.352 --> 35:23.724
and I'm livin'
at 206 Mayfield,
Apartment 5E.

35:24.991 --> 35:27.193
That's all true.

35:28.629 --> 35:32.498
Okay then. I guess
I'll be hearing from you.

35:39.606 --> 35:41.374
[ Line Rings ]

35:41.441 --> 35:43.910
♪♪♪♪ [ Disco ]
Dahlia?

35:45.311 --> 35:48.649
Dahlia,
where the hell are you?

35:48.715 --> 35:51.084
Oh, baby, thank God.

35:51.151 --> 35:55.789
Listen. You know I told you
about the, uh‐‐ my friend
who knew the parole officer?

35:55.856 --> 35:57.658
Well, it's great because‐‐

35:57.724 --> 36:00.026
Jesus Christ, Dahlia.
For the love of God,

36:00.093 --> 36:03.664
do not tell me
that you've been talking to
your parole officer.

36:03.730 --> 36:06.667
No. Um‐‐

36:06.733 --> 36:11.605
I just think
if we could do, you know,
one honest thing‐‐

36:11.672 --> 36:14.875
just one thing
that we know is true, Wayne.

36:14.941 --> 36:19.580
Dahlia, parole is
the tip of the iceberg here.

36:19.646 --> 36:21.715
You know that.

36:21.782 --> 36:24.551
We are committing
a list of crimes here
as long as my goddamn arm.

36:24.618 --> 36:26.953
We do not want
to involve the law.

36:27.020 --> 36:28.955
Right.

36:31.124 --> 36:32.659
Okay.

36:36.997 --> 36:38.965
How was your day?

36:39.032 --> 36:43.336
Fine.
[ Breathing Heavily ]

36:43.403 --> 36:46.072
Dale is worming his way
into all the meetings.

36:46.139 --> 36:48.441
Hugh is drunk off his ass.

36:48.509 --> 36:53.279
And, uh, I think I just screwed
a whole bunch of Katrina victims
out of their future.

37:01.221 --> 37:03.189
I love you.

37:03.256 --> 37:05.692
Yeah, I love you too.

37:17.504 --> 37:19.706
[ Cell Phone Beeps ]

37:21.007 --> 37:25.679
♪♪ And if you find it
hard to breathe ♪♪

37:25.746 --> 37:28.782
♪♪ I'll be the air
that fills your lungs ♪♪

37:28.849 --> 37:31.785
♪♪ 'Cause you can lose
your faith ♪♪

37:31.852 --> 37:33.854
[ Owl Hoots ]
♪♪♪♪ [ Continues ]

37:40.761 --> 37:43.864
You should know I have backing
from powerful forces.

37:45.065 --> 37:47.367
[ Cheering On TV ]

37:48.535 --> 37:50.904
What I'm saying
is you will not survive.

37:50.971 --> 37:55.041
"'‘‘And haven't you
your own land to visit,'
continued Miss Ivors,

37:55.108 --> 37:59.580
'‘‘that you know nothing
of your own people
and your own country.'"

37:59.646 --> 38:02.616
What in the hell
is that supposed to mean?

38:02.683 --> 38:04.885
It's from The Dead by Joyce.

38:08.421 --> 38:10.423
You've never heard of Joyce?

38:10.490 --> 38:13.026
'Course I have.
She's one of
my favorite writers.

38:14.494 --> 38:16.730
You gotta get educated,
Ginny.

38:16.797 --> 38:19.533
That's how
they keep you down.
[ Scoffs ]

38:19.600 --> 38:22.903
Like you ever been
to third grade.

38:22.969 --> 38:25.071
Bachelor of arts
in English literature,

38:25.138 --> 38:28.975
‐ master's in philosophy,
University of Phoenix.
‐ You've never been to Phoenix.

38:29.042 --> 38:34.147
Phoenix come to me
right there
in the state pen.

38:34.214 --> 38:37.551
Such is the power
of the Internet.

38:37.618 --> 38:40.386
<i>It's a new world, Ginny.</i>

38:40.453 --> 38:42.789
[ Baby Fusses ]
"We are living
in a skeptical...

38:42.856 --> 38:48.094
and, if I may use the phrase,
a thought‐tormented age."

38:48.161 --> 38:51.397
It's beautiful.

38:51.464 --> 38:54.100
It's about how
we've lost our souls.

38:54.167 --> 38:56.402
[ Cheering On TV ]
[ Man On TV ] Coming up‐‐
[ Continues, Indistinct ]

38:56.469 --> 38:59.540
You feel that,
don't you, Ginny?

39:00.574 --> 39:02.676
That emptiness.

39:05.278 --> 39:07.247
Right here.

39:07.313 --> 39:10.483
♪♪♪♪ [ Rock ]

39:10.551 --> 39:12.953
[ Owl Hoots ]

39:19.560 --> 39:22.863
♪♪ The fox
The fox ♪♪
[ Sighs ]

39:22.929 --> 39:26.199
♪♪ Lied ♪♪

39:26.266 --> 39:29.570
♪♪ Eyes on the wrong prize ♪♪

39:32.305 --> 39:36.276
♪♪ The fox
The fox ♪♪

39:36.342 --> 39:38.378
♪♪ Lied ♪♪

39:38.444 --> 39:41.982
♪♪ Fox eyes
on the wrong prize ♪♪

39:45.719 --> 39:48.088
♪♪ We're in a different war ♪♪

39:48.154 --> 39:51.424
♪♪ With ourselves
and with some of you ♪♪

39:51.491 --> 39:54.160
♪♪ So many things
that don't ♪♪

39:54.227 --> 39:57.664
♪♪ Hold true ♪♪

39:57.731 --> 40:03.003
♪♪ With the fear
that dims our light ♪♪

40:04.204 --> 40:06.940
♪♪ With the barnacles on ♪♪

40:07.007 --> 40:09.743
♪♪ Our right ♪♪

40:12.012 --> 40:16.149
[ Male Announcer On TV,
Indistinct ]

40:16.216 --> 40:19.620
‐ ♪♪ On the grass ♪♪
‐ ♪♪ On the grass ♪♪

40:19.686 --> 40:21.755
♪♪ On the beachy head ♪♪

40:23.189 --> 40:28.995
♪♪ On the cliff
to which you've been led ♪♪

40:29.062 --> 40:34.601
♪♪ The curve of the hill
is green and soft ♪♪

40:34.668 --> 40:37.571
[ TV Continues, Indistinct ]
♪♪ As if the wind ♪♪

40:37.638 --> 40:40.173
I thought
you were with Cael.
I was.

40:40.240 --> 40:42.576
So where is he?

40:42.643 --> 40:44.945
[ Soft Chuckle ]

40:45.011 --> 40:49.249
I don't know.
♪♪ You'll sail alone ♪♪

40:49.315 --> 40:51.752
♪♪ If you don't hold the rope ♪♪

40:51.818 --> 40:56.056
♪♪ You'll go alone ♪♪♪♪
